    "answer": "Based on recent sources, paying for external research for a new agent CFO project can be justified if it enhances decision-making, efficiency, or strategic insights. Cost-benefit analysis (CBA) frameworks suggest that external research can provide valuable, unbiased data that supports sound financial decisions ([Paro](https://paro.ai/blog/mastering-cost-benefit-analysis), [Corporate Finance Institute](https://corporatefinanceinstitute.com/resources/accounting/cost-benefit-analysis)). \n\nIf internal resources lack the necessary expertise, credibility, or capacity—especially for complex or specialized research—outsourcing may be more efficient and cost-effective ([Relevant Insights](https://www.relevantinsights.com/articles/when-is-it-time-for-outsourcing-research), [Lab42](https://www.lab42.com/blog/when-to-outsource-market-research-vs-keeping-it-in-house-a-decision-making-framework)). \n\nGiven the current availability of targeted, high-quality research options and the importance of accurate data for a CFO project, purchasing external research is justified if it provides significant strategic value or risk mitigation. \n\n**Recommendation:** Proceed with external research if it offers a clear advantage in decision quality, saves internal resources, or reduces risk. Otherwise, consider internal or alternative data sources.",
