    "answer": "Based on recent insights, paying for external research for a new agent CFO project can be justified if it offers significant value in terms of speed, breadth of sources, and cost efficiency. External research agencies or AI-powered research agents can deliver comprehensive, cited reports in hours rather than weeks, saving time and internal resources ([ClawGig](https://clawgig.ai/use-cases/research)). \n\nHowever, consider the opportunity cost of internal team time and expertise. If your team lacks the necessary skills or capacity, outsourcing can provide reliable, high-quality insights without overburdening internal staff ([Relevant Insights](https://www.relevantinsights.com/articles/when-is-it-time-for-outsourcing-research), [Lab42](https://www.lab42.com/blog/when-to-outsource-market-research-vs-keeping-it-in-house-a-decision-making-framework)). \n\nGiven the high failure rates of internal AI builds and the complexity involved, leveraging external research—especially AI-driven—may be more cost-effective and less risky than building in-house ([Tributary AI](https://www.thetributary.ai/blog/build-vs-buy-ai-decision-guide)). \n\n**Recommendation:** If the project requires rapid, broad, and reliable insights, and internal resources are limited or lack expertise, outsourcing research is justified. Otherwise, if you have capable internal teams and low urgency, internal research could suffice. Overall, external research appears to be a justified investment for a new CFO project to ensure timely and credible data.",
