    "answer": "The current state of gasless transaction infrastructure on Status Network centers around the implementation of zero-knowledge-based solutions, primarily utilizing RLN (Rate Limiting Nullifier), which replaces traditional gas fees with cryptographic rate limits enforced via zero-knowledge proofs and secret sharing ([Status Network Documentation, 12/16/2025](https://docs.status.network/general-info/gasless-transactions)). Status Network has successfully launched a fully gasless Layer 2 on the Linea zkEVM stack, enabling users to transact without paying gas, funded by yield from bridged assets and native app revenues, thus removing reliance on sequencer fees and traditional gas models ([Status Network Blog, 07/09/2025](https://our.status.im/status-network-first-gasless-l2)). The infrastructure emphasizes privacy, spam protection, and economic sustainability through yield-backed models.\n\nIn comparison, EIP-4337 (Account Abstraction) approaches, such as those discussed in recent proposals and implementations, focus on enabling smart contract wallets with customizable validation and payment logic, including optional paymasters that sponsor gas ([Our.status.im, 03/07/2026](https://our.status.im/what-is-account-abstraction)). EIP-4337 operates entirely through smart contracts and bundlers, allowing features like batching, flexible validation, and sponsored transactions without changing the core protocol. Notably, the standard has been live and evolving, with multiple versions and extensions (e.g., EIP-7702, ERC-7562) supporting advanced account management and privacy features ([7BlockLabs, 01/05/2026](https://www.7blocklabs.com/blog/eip-4337-account-abstraction-status-2026-vs-erc-4337-account-abstraction-status-2026)).\n\nWhile Status's gasless infrastructure leverages zero-knowledge cryptography and yield-backed economic models to eliminate gas fees at the Layer 2 level, ERC-4337 provides a flexible, protocol-agnostic framework for account abstraction that can support gas sponsorship, batching, and custom validation rules via smart contracts. Both approaches aim to improve user experience and scalability but differ significantly in their technical mechanisms: Status's solution is deeply integrated with zkEVM and cryptographic spam prevention, whereas ERC-4337 emphasizes programmable, contract-based account logic that can incorporate sponsored transactions ([Status Network Blog, 03/04/2026](https://status.network/blog/status-network-economic-model-yield-funding-pool-and-zero-gas)).",
