    "answer": "Bankr's LLM gateway routing strategies suggest that the decision for an agent CFO to choose Claude over GPT models hinges on the specific reasoning tasks and budget constraints. According to recent research, GPT models like GPT-4o are generally more cost-effective for tasks requiring high throughput and general reasoning, especially at scale, with lower per-token costs (e.g., $2.50/$10 per 1M tokens for GPT-4o) ([Result 1](https://www.getmonetizely.com/articles/claude-pro-vs-gpt-4-plus-pricing-costs-limits-and-value-for-power-users), [Result 9](https://atxp.ai/blog/claude-vs-gpt4-agent-workloads)). \n\nHowever, Claude excels in high-stakes reasoning, complex analysis, and technical writing, with models like Claude Sonnet 3.7 demonstrating superior performance in long-context reasoning (up to 200K tokens) and advanced reasoning capabilities ([Result 9](https://atxp.ai/blog/claude-vs-gpt4-agent-workloads)). For budget-constrained reasoning tasks that demand deep analytical or technical reasoning, Claude's specialized models may provide better accuracy and reliability, justifying potentially higher costs or specific use-case suitability. \n\nRouting strategies further support this choice by recommending dynamic model selection: simple, cost-sensitive queries can be routed to cheaper models like GPT-4o Mini, while complex reasoning tasks are directed to Claude's advanced models ([Result 8](https://zylos.ai/research/2026-03-02-ai-agent-model-routing), [Result 10](https://www.burnwise.io/blog/llm-model-routing-guide)). In summary, an agent CFO should consider Claude when the task involves high-stakes reasoning, technical accuracy, or long-context understanding, and when the budget allows for the higher per-query cost compared to more general-purpose GPT models.",
