    "answer": "The security model of ERC-8004 agent identity registries is designed to enable trustless interactions between autonomous agents on-chain by leveraging a layered approach to identity, reputation, and validation. The core component, the Identity Registry, is built on ERC-721, providing each agent with a portable, verifiable on-chain identity that is resistant to censorship and phishing attacks through domain verification ([panewslab](https://www.panewslab.com/en/articles/019cbd37-e329-7216-886b-fb1d00fa5008)). This registry ensures that agents can be reliably discovered and their identities authenticated without relying on pre-existing trust, forming a foundational trust anchor ([composable-security](https://composable-security.com/blog/erc-8004-a-practical-explainer-for-trustless-agents)).\n\nComplementing the identity registry, ERC-8004 incorporates reputation and validation registries that facilitate trust through feedback signals and cryptoeconomic or cryptographic validation methods such as stake-secured re-execution, zkML proofs, or trusted execution environments (TEEs). These mechanisms allow agents to establish trustworthiness dynamically, based on verifiable reputation scores and third-party validation, which can be layered according to the risk level of the transaction. This modular trust model supports secure, trustless interactions across organizational boundaries, enabling agents to operate without pre-established relationships ([ethereum.org](https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-8004), [oasis.net](https://oasis.net/blog/erc-8004-trustless-agents)).\n\nOverall, ERC-8004's security architecture promotes trust through cryptographically secure identity verification, feedback-based reputation systems, and flexible validation protocols, making it suitable for a wide range of on-chain interactions where trust is established through verifiable credentials rather than reliance on centralized authorities ([timerring](https://blogs.timerring.com/posts/erc-8004-trustless-agents), [datawallet](https://www.datawallet.com/crypto/erc-8004-explained)).",
